00:00:18,769 --> 00:00:20,290
It's not. It's not.

5
00:00:21,531 --> 00:00:27,336
On Call of Duty World War II, we wanted to build something that offered a lot of new social and creative outlets for players,

6
00:00:27,616 --> 00:00:29,157
and we created Headquarters.

7
00:00:30,158 --> 00:00:35,642
Headquarters is a large multiplayer social space that allows players to gear up,

8
00:00:35,882 --> 00:00:40,506
check out various challenges, test out their weapons, play mini-games, and a whole lot more.

9
00:00:41,247 --> 00:00:43,247
It's loosely themed around D-Day Plus Three,

10
00:00:43,328 --> 00:00:45,228
three days after the invasion of Normandy.

11
00:00:45,949 --> 00:00:48,450
And it's a military base where players can stay

12
00:00:48,910 --> 00:00:50,191
wrapped up in our game world

13
00:00:50,371 --> 00:00:52,171
while still interacting with core systems.

14
00:00:52,872 --> 00:00:54,252
In a way, it's an evolution

15
00:00:54,432 --> 00:00:56,914
of Call of Duty Advanced Warfare's virtual lobby.

16
00:00:57,414 --> 00:00:58,954
A semi-interactive menu

17
00:00:59,335 --> 00:01:01,716
that let people customize their characters

18
00:01:02,156 --> 00:01:03,276
and then show them off to people

19
00:01:03,316 --> 00:01:04,377
that they'll be in a match with

20
00:01:04,437 --> 00:01:05,958
and see what everyone else has equipped.

21
00:01:07,211 --> 00:01:08,592
We had a lot of goals setting out.

22
00:01:09,292 --> 00:01:13,777
What we wanted to offer players, how we wanted to engender specific behavior, and how we

23
00:01:13,817 --> 00:01:15,818
wanted to improve the typical player session.

24
00:01:16,559 --> 00:01:21,143
We were successful in some ways, unsuccessful in others, and ultimately learned a lot along

25
00:01:21,163 --> 00:01:26,648
the way about how mostly non-combative features can resonate with a combat-focused player

26
00:01:26,688 --> 00:01:27,669
base when done right.

27
00:01:29,469 --> 00:01:33,051
We'll examine Headquarters from a design perspective, from start to finish.

28
00:01:33,832 --> 00:01:34,992
What were our goals setting out?

29
00:01:35,413 --> 00:01:37,314
How did we set out to achieve those goals?

30
00:01:37,754 --> 00:01:42,337
And what were ultimately the results, positive and negative, on the final player experience?

31
00:01:43,457 --> 00:01:45,539
In between we're going to take a close look at a system, Orders and Contracts, which is

32
00:01:45,559 --> 00:01:47,380
a familiar system with a bit of a spin, and wrap things up with some final thoughts on

